NANO(1)                          User Commands                         NANO(1)

NAME
       nano - Nano's ANOther editor, inspired by Pico

SYNOPSIS
       nano [OPTIONS] [[+LINE[,COLUMN]] FILE]...

DESCRIPTION
       nano is a small and friendly text editor.  It copies the look and feel
       of Pico, but is free software, and implements several features that
       Pico lacks, such as: opening multiple files, scrolling per line,
       undo/redo, syntax coloring, line numbering, and soft-wrapping of
       overlong lines.

       When giving a filename on the command line, the cursor can be put on a
       specific line by adding the line number with a plus sign (+) before the
       filename, and even in a specific column by adding it with a comma.

       If the first file specified is a dash (-), nano will read data from
       standard input.

OPTIONS
       -A, --smarthome
              Make the Home key smarter.

       -B, --backup
              When saving a file, back up the previous version of it, using
              the current filename suffixed with a tilde (~).

       -C dir, --backupdir=dir
              Make and keep not just one backup file, but make a uniquely
              numbered one every time a file is saved.

       -E, --tabstospaces
              Convert typed tabs to spaces.

       -G, --locking
              Use vim-style file locking when editing files.

       -H, --historylog
              Save the last hundred search strings and replacement strings
              and executed commands, so they can be easily reused.

       -I, --ignorercfiles
              Don't look at the system's nanorc nor at the user's nanorc.

       -J number, --guidestripe=number
              Draw a vertical stripe at the given column.

       -K, --rawsequences
              Interpret escape sequences directly.

       -L, --nonewlines
              Don't automatically add a newline when a text does not end
              with one.

       -M, --trimblanks
              Snip trailing whitespace from the wrapped line when automatic
              hard-wrapping occurs or when text is justified.

       -N, --noconvert
              Disable automatic conversion of files from DOS/Mac format.

       -P, --positionlog
              Save the cursor position of files between editing sessions.

       -Q "regex", --quotestr="regex"
              Set the regular expression for matching the quoting part of a
              line.

       -R, --restricted
              Restricted mode: don't allow suspending, or saving a file
              under a different name, or appending/prepending to a file.

       -S, --softwrap
              Display over-long lines on multiple screen rows.

       -T number, --tabsize=number
              Set the size (width) of a tab to number columns.

       -V, --version
              Show the current version number and exit.

       -W, --wordbounds
              Detect word boundaries differently.

       -Y name, --syntax=name
              Use the named syntax for syntax highlighting.

       -Z, --zap
              Let an unmodified Backspace or Delete erase the marked region.

       -a, --atblanks
              When doing soft line wrapping, wrap lines at blank characters.

       -b, --breaklonglines
              Automatically hard-wrap the current line when it becomes
              overlong.

       -c, --constantshow
              Constantly show the cursor position on the status bar.

       -d, --rebinddelete
              Interpret the Delete and Backspace keys differently.

       -e, --emptyline
              Do not use the line below the title bar.

       -g, --showcursor
              Make the cursor visible in the file browser and help viewer.

       -h, --help
              Show a summary of the available command-line options and exit.

       -i, --autoindent
              Automatically indent a newly created line to the same number
              of tabs and/or spaces as the previous line.

       -j, --jumpyscrolling
              Scroll the buffer contents per half-screen instead of per line.

       -k, --cutfromcursor
              Make Ctrl+K cut from the cursor to end of line.

       -l, --linenumbers
              Display line numbers to the left of the text area.

       -m, --mouse
              Enable mouse support, if available.

       -n, --noread
              Treat any name given on the command line as a new file.

       -o dir, --operatingdir=dir
              Set the operating directory.

       -p, --preserve
              Preserve the XON and XOFF sequences (^Q and ^S).

       -r number, --fill=number
              Set the target width for justifying and automatic
              hard-wrapping at this number of columns.

       -s program, --speller=program
              Use this alternative spell checker command.

       -t, --saveonexit
              Save a changed buffer without prompting.

       -v, --view
              Just view the file and disallow editing.

       -w, --nowrap
              Do not automatically hard-wrap the current line when it becomes
              overlong. (Old short option for -b's opposite.)

       -x, --nohelp
              Don't show the two help lines at the bottom of the screen.

       -y, --afterends
              Make Ctrl+Right and Ctrl+Delete stop at word ends instead of
              beginnings.

       -%, --stateflags
              Use the top-right corner of the screen for showing some state
              flags.

       -_, --minibar
              Suppress the title bar and instead show information about the
              current buffer at the bottom of the screen.

TOGGLES
       Several of the above options can be switched on and off also while
       nano is running. See the internal help text (^G) for a list.

DEFAULT SHORTCUTS
       ^G     (F1)            Display this help text
       ^X     (F2)            Close the current file buffer / Exit from nano
       ^O     (F3)            Write the current file to disk
       ^R     (F5)            Insert another file into current buffer

       ^W     (F6)            Search for a string or a regular expression
       ^\     (M-R)           Replace a string or a regular expression
       ^K     (F9)            Cut current line and store it in cutbuffer
       ^U     (F10)           Paste from the cutbuffer into current line

       ^T                     Execute a function or an external command
       ^J     (F4)            Justify the current paragraph

       ^C     (F11)           Display the position of the cursor
       ^_     (F13)           Go to line and column number

       M-U                    Undo the last operation
       M-E                    Redo the last undone operation

FILES
       /etc/nanorc
              System-wide configuration file (not used on LikeOS).

       ~/.nanorc
              Per-user configuration file.

NOTES
       This is a port of GNU nano 8.3 to LikeOS.
       Some features may be limited compared to the full Linux version.
       UTF-8 support is not enabled.

SEE ALSO
       The nano homepage: https://nano-editor.org/

       The full documentation for nano is maintained as a Texinfo manual.

